    fact: 'Realism (1840s–1880s) rejected idealized history painting for honest depictions of ordinary modern life, often with political intent. Gustave Courbet\'s monumental "The Stone Breakers" (1849) and "A Burial at Ornans" (1850) placed peasants at the scale traditionally reserved for mythological heroes — a radical class statement. Jean-François Millet\'s "The Gleaners" (1857) dignified agricultural labor with quiet grandeur. Honoré Daumier\'s lithographs skewered political hypocrisy. In Russia, the Wanderers (Peredvizhniki) took art outside academic walls to expose social injustice. Key artists: Courbet, Millet, Daumier, Corot, Rosa Bonheur.',
