  // ── TECHNIQUES ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Chiaroscuro',
    subtitle: 'Light & Shadow',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/The_Calling_of_Saint_Matthew-Caravaggo_%281599-1600%29.jpg/800px-The_Calling_of_Saint_Matthew-Caravaggo_%281599-1600%29.jpg',
    fact: 'From Italian "chiaro" (light) and "oscuro" (dark), chiaroscuro describes the use of strong tonal contrast to model three-dimensional form on a two-dimensional surface. Leonardo da Vinci developed subtle gradations; Caravaggio radicalized it into tenebrism — extreme darkness punctured by single spotlit figures, as in "The Calling of Saint Matthew" (1600). Rembrandt used chiaroscuro to reveal interior psychological complexity, figures emerging from warm amber shadow. The technique directly shaped the aesthetic of cinema — German Expressionist film and film noir both owe it an enormous debt. Key practitioners: Leonardo, Caravaggio, Rembrandt, Goya.',
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Sfumato',
    subtitle: 'Smoky Transitions',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Mona_Lisa%2C_by_Leonardo_da_Vinci%2C_from_C2RMF_retouched.jpg/800px-Mona_Lisa%2C_by_Leonardo_da_Vinci%2C_from_C2RMF_retouched.jpg',
    fact: 'Leonardo da Vinci\'s own term (from Italian "fumo," smoke) for blending oil glazes so gradually that contours become imperceptible, replaced by atmospheric haze. Applied with near-transparent layers dried one by one, sfumato creates the mysterious depth of the Mona Lisa\'s smile and the receding landscape behind her — a dreamlike spatial ambiguity that no prior painter had achieved. Leonardo described it as painting "without lines or borders, in the manner of smoke or beyond the focus plane." The Mona Lisa\'s glazes may number in the dozens, each applied and cured before the next. Key practitioner: Leonardo da Vinci, with echoes in Correggio.',
