    fact: 'True fresco (buon fresco) involves applying pigment suspended in water directly onto fresh, wet lime plaster. As the plaster carbonates, it chemically bonds the pigment into the wall permanently. Michelangelo painted the Sistine Chapel ceiling (1508–12) this way — lying on scaffolding for four years — working in sections (giornate) that had to be completed before the plaster set. The demanding medium requires fast, confident work but rewards the painter with extraordinary durability: well-executed frescoes can outlast millennia. Key artists: Giotto, Masaccio, Michelangelo, Raphael, Diego Rivera.',
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Impasto',
    subtitle: 'Sculptural Paint',
