    fact: 'Impasto (Italian: "dough" or "paste") describes oil paint applied so thickly that brushstrokes or palette-knife marks leave a sculptural, three-dimensional texture. Van Gogh\'s turbulent skies and swirling cypresses are built up in dense ridges that catch raking light dynamically, making the painted surface itself as expressive as the subject. Rembrandt used selective impasto in highlights — jewels and lace — to draw the eye. In the twentieth century, Frank Auerbach built layers to near-sculptural density over months of reworking. The technique celebrates the raw materiality of paint as subject. Key artists: Van Gogh, Rembrandt, Monet, Courbet, Auerbach.',
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Pointillism',
    subtitle: 'Optical Color Mixing',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/A_Sunday_on_La_Grande_Jatte%2C_Georges_Seurat%2C_1884.jpg/1280px-A_Sunday_on_La_Grande_Jatte%2C_Georges_Seurat%2C_1884.jpg',
    fact: 'Developed by Georges Seurat and Paul Signac from 1886, Pointillism (also called Divisionism) applies tiny dots of pure unmixed color side by side, relying on the viewer\'s eye to blend them optically at a distance into luminous, vibrating tones. Seurat\'s "A Sunday Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte" (1884–86) — nearly 10 feet wide — was constructed from thousands of touches after years of preparatory studies. The method was grounded in color science: theorists Chevreul and Rood had demonstrated that juxtaposed complementaries intensify each other. Seurat called his method "Chromoluminarism." Key artists: Georges Seurat, Paul Signac, Henri-Edmond Cross.',
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Collage',
    subtitle: 'Assembled Fragments',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Juan_Gris_-_Portrait_of_Pablo_Picasso_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/800px-Juan_Gris_-_Portrait_of_Pablo_Picasso_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg',
    fact: 'Collage (from French "coller," to glue) became a serious fine-art technique when Picasso and Braque incorporated newspaper clippings, wallpaper, and printed labels into Synthetic Cubist works around 1912, blurring the hierarchy between fine art and everyday printed matter. Kurt Schwitters elevated scavenged urban refuse into monumental "Merz" constructions. Hannah Höch and John Heartfield weaponized photomontage as political critique of Weimar Germany and rising fascism. Joseph Cornell enclosed enigmatic ephemera in dreamlike shadow boxes. Today collage thrives in both physical and digital forms. Key artists: Picasso, Braque, Schwitters, Höch, Heartfield, Cornell.',
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Tempera',
    subtitle: 'Egg & Pigment',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/26/Sandro_Botticelli_046.jpg/1280px-Sandro_Botticelli_046.jpg',
    fact: 'Egg tempera — pigment suspended in egg yolk — was the dominant European panel-painting medium from the 13th through the 15th century. It dries within seconds and cannot be blended wet-in-wet; form is built through fine parallel hatching strokes, creating a crystalline, graphic surface quality. Botticelli\'s "The Birth of Venus" and "Primavera" are tempera paintings — their luminous linearity inseparable from the medium\'s character. Jan van Eyck\'s development of flexible oil paint in the 1420s gradually superseded tempera, though Andrew Wyeth\'s 20th-century works ("Christina\'s World") demonstrate its enduring power. Key artists: Giotto, Duccio, Botticelli, Piero della Francesca, Wyeth.',
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Encaustic',
    subtitle: 'Molten Wax',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Fayum_egyptian_funerary_portrait_1627_NAMAthens.jpg/600px-Fayum_egyptian_funerary_portrait_1627_NAMAthens.jpg',
    fact: 'Encaustic painting uses heated beeswax mixed with pigment and resin, applied hot and fused with a heated tool to a rigid surface. The Fayum mummy portraits (1st–3rd century CE, Roman Egypt) are masterpieces of the medium: astonishingly lifelike faces of extraordinary directness and psychological immediacy that feel utterly contemporary. Encaustic lay dormant for centuries until Jasper Johns revived it in the 1950s for his "Flag" and "Target" paintings, exploiting wax\'s translucency — earlier layers visible through the surface, earlier gestures preserved like amber. Key artists: Anonymous Fayum masters, Jasper Johns.',
  },
