    medium: 'Oil on canvas',
    location: 'Rijksmuseum, Amsterdam',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/The_Night_Watch_-_HD.jpg/800px-The_Night_Watch_-_HD.jpg',
    description: 'Rembrandt\'s largest and most celebrated work depicts Captain Frans Banninck Cocq\'s Amsterdam civic guard company in a moment of dynamic movement — a radical departure from the static group portrait customary for such militia commissions. Captain Cocq\'s dark figure steps forward against his lieutenant\'s brilliant yellow coat; a mysterious girl with a dead cockerel glows at center-left. The painting was trimmed on all four sides in the 18th century to fit a wall. Its current title — a 19th-century nickname from its darkened varnish — is a misnomer: it depicts a daytime scene.',
  },
  {
    title: 'The Great Wave off Kanagawa',
    artist: 'Katsushika Hokusai',
    year: 'c. 1831',
    medium: 'Woodblock print (ukiyo-e)',
    location: 'Multiple collections worldwide',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Tsunami_by_hokusai_19th_century.jpg/1280px-Tsunami_by_hokusai_19th_century.jpg',
    description: 'From Hokusai\'s landmark series "Thirty-six Views of Mount Fuji," this woodblock print is perhaps the single most reproduced artwork in history. The enormous hollow wave — its claw-like foam fingertips framing tiny fishing boats and distant, serene Fuji — compresses terror and beauty into the formal language of ukiyo-e: bold Prussian blue (imported from Europe), flat color areas, dynamic asymmetric composition. Hokusai was 71 when he made it. He is said to have declared at 90: "If only Heaven will give me just ten more years — just five — I will yet become a true artist."',
  },
  {
    title: 'The Arnolfini Portrait',
    artist: 'Jan van Eyck',
    year: '1434',
    medium: 'Oil on oak panel',
    location: 'National Gallery, London',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/Van_Eyck_-_Arnolfini_Portrait.jpg/800px-Van_Eyck_-_Arnolfini_Portrait.jpg',
    description: 'One of the most technically accomplished paintings of the 15th century, van Eyck\'s double portrait of Giovanni di Nicolao Arnolfini demonstrates the transformative optical capabilities of oil paint van Eyck helped perfect. Every surface — fur, polished bronze, mirror glass, candle flame — is rendered with microscopic fidelity. The convex mirror on the back wall reflects the room from the opposite direction, revealing two additional witnesses — one possibly the painter, whose inscription reads: "Jan van Eyck was here. 1434." Whether the painting documents a marriage contract has been debated by scholars for decades.',
  },
  {
    title: 'American Gothic',
    artist: 'Grant Wood',
    year: '1930',
    medium: 'Oil on beaverboard',
    location: 'Art Institute of Chicago',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/Grant_Wood_-_American_Gothic_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/800px-Grant_Wood_-_American_Gothic_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg',
    description: 'One of the most parodied images in American art, this painting depicts a farmer and his daughter before an Iowa Carpenter Gothic house in Eldon, Iowa — painted after Wood saw the house and "fancied the kind of people who should live in that house." His models were his sister Nan Wood Graham and his dentist, Dr. Byron McKeeby. Nan objected to being portrayed as a wife rather than a daughter. Intended as neither satire nor pure celebration, American Gothic has been read as both a dignified tribute to Depression-era rural stoicism and a deadpan critique of Midwestern puritanism.',
  },
];

const philosophers = [
  {
    name: 'Plato',
    dates: '428–348 BCE',
    descriptor: 'Ideal Forms & the Suspicion of Art',
    quote: 'Beauty is the splendor of truth.',
    thought: 'For Plato, art is mimesis — a copy of a copy, twice removed from the eternal Forms that constitute true reality. Painters depict beds; beds are themselves copies of the ideal Form of Bed. Yet the "Symposium" presents beauty as the most visible of all Forms: a ladder ascending from physical to absolute Beauty itself. Plato\'s deep ambivalence — banishing poets from the Republic, yet filling his own dialogues with myth and imagery — has shaped debates about art and truth for two millennia.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Aristotle',
    dates: '384–322 BCE',
    descriptor: 'Mimesis, Catharsis & the Pleasure of Imitation',
    quote: 'Art represents not the outward appearance of things, but their inward significance.',
    thought: 'In the "Poetics," Aristotle rehabilitated art from Plato\'s suspicion. Mimesis is a fundamental human pleasure: we learn even from representations of painful subjects. Tragedy — the highest art form — achieves catharsis: a clarifying purging of pity and fear through the fall of a noble protagonist. Art imitates not what is, but what could be, making it more philosophical than history. Aristotle\'s concept of catharsis has shaped every theory of drama from the Renaissance through Brecht.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Immanuel Kant',
    dates: '1724–1804',
    descriptor: 'Aesthetic Judgment & the Sublime',
    quote: 'The beautiful is that which pleases universally without a concept.',
    thought: 'Kant\'s "Critique of Judgment" (1790) established the modern philosophical framework for aesthetics. The judgment "this is beautiful" is subjective yet claims universal assent — we don\'t merely like the beautiful; we demand that others find it beautiful too. Kant also distinguishes the beautiful (formal, disinterested pleasure) from the sublime: the overwhelming vastness or power that initially defeats imagination but ultimately reveals the superiority of moral reason within us. The sublime became Romanticism\'s defining obsession.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Georg Hegel',
    dates: '1770–1831',
    descriptor: 'Art as Absolute Spirit & the End of Art',
    quote: 'Art is the sensuous shining of the Idea.',
    thought: 'For Hegel, art, religion, and philosophy are the three forms through which Absolute Spirit comes to know itself. The history of art is Spirit progressively freeing itself from matter: Symbolic art (Egyptian — meaning exceeds form), Classical (Greek — form and content in perfect balance), Romantic (Christian — infinite spiritual content bursting finite material). Hegel provocatively declared the "end of art" — not its death, but its supersession by philosophy as the highest vehicle of self-knowledge.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Friedrich Nietzsche',
    dates: '1844–1900',
    descriptor: 'Apollo, Dionysus & Life-Affirming Art',
    quote: 'We have art in order not to die of the truth.',
    thought: '"The Birth of Tragedy" (1872) proposed that Greek art arose from tension between two primal drives: the Apollonian (clarity, form, individuation — sculpture, epic) and the Dionysian (intoxication, self-dissolution — music, tragedy). Great art needs both: Apollonian form shapes Dionysian energy; Dionysian force animates Apollonian surfaces. For Nietzsche, art is the supreme life-affirming force — not a mirror of reality, but a beautifying transformation that makes existence bearable and even glorious.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Arthur Schopenhauer',
    dates: '1788–1860',
    descriptor: 'Art as Liberation from the Will',
    quote: 'Music expresses that which cannot be said and on which it is impossible to be silent.',
    thought: 'In "The World as Will and Representation" (1818), Schopenhauer argues that art offers temporary liberation from the relentless, suffering-causing Will underlying all existence. When we contemplate great art we become pure knowing subjects, freed momentarily from desire. Music stands apart from all other arts: while painting and poetry copy Platonic Ideas, music directly expresses the Will itself — the innermost nature of reality. This is why music moves us so profoundly. Schopenhauer\'s aesthetics profoundly influenced Wagner, Nietzsche, Proust, and Thomas Mann.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Walter Benjamin',
    dates: '1892–1940',
    descriptor: 'Aura, Reproduction & the Politics of Art',
    quote: 'That which withers in the age of mechanical reproduction is the aura of the work of art.',
    thought: 'Benjamin\'s 1935 essay "The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction" argued that photography and film shatter art\'s unique "aura" — its quality of authentic, singular presence in time and space, rooted in ritual and place. Mechanical reproduction democratizes culture but also enables fascism\'s aestheticization of politics. His concept of aura remains the essential reference for every debate about authenticity, originality, and digital reproduction — as urgent today as when he wrote it fleeing Nazi Europe.',
  },
  {
    name: 'John Dewey',
    dates: '1859–1952',
    descriptor: 'Art as Experience & Democratic Aesthetics',
    quote: 'Art is the living and concrete proof that man is capable of restoring consciously the union of sense, need, impulse and action.',
    thought: 'Dewey\'s "Art as Experience" (1934) attacked the museum culture that places art on a pedestal, severing it from the living experience that generated it. Aesthetic experience is not a special category reserved for high art — it is the heightened form of any meaningful, fulfilling activity: cooking, a well-pitched conversation, a craftsman\'s absorbed work. Great art grows from and returns to the fabric of ordinary life. Dewey\'s pragmatist aesthetics shaped democratic education theory and participatory art movements.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Simone de Beauvoir',
    dates: '1908–1986',
    descriptor: 'Art, Freedom & the Gendered Gaze',
    quote: 'The work of art is not a copy of reality but a reality of its own.',
    thought: 'De Beauvoir\'s existentialist aesthetics, developed alongside her feminist analysis in "The Second Sex" (1949), examined how art has historically represented women as passive objects of the male gaze rather than active subjects. Great art, for de Beauvoir, is a project of freedom — an act through which artist and viewer transcend given conditions and assume responsibility for meaning-making. Art created from bad faith — uncritically accepting social roles — merely reflects, rather than transforms, structures of oppression.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Martin Heidegger',
    dates: '1889–1976',
    descriptor: 'Art as the Setting-Itself-to-Work of Truth',
    quote: 'Art is the setting-itself-to-work of truth.',
    thought: 'Heidegger\'s lectures "The Origin of the Work of Art" (1935–36) propose that great art does not represent the world — it opens up a world. Van Gogh\'s painting of peasant shoes lets their "equipmental being" — their relation to a world of labor and earth — become visible for the first time. The work creates a strife between World (human meaning-structures) and Earth (material resistance). Architecture and poetry, for Heidegger, are the most fundamental arts: not decorations, but the founding of a human dwelling.',
  },
];

const quizQuestions = [
  {
    category: 'Techniques',
    q: 'Which technique did Leonardo da Vinci invent to blend oil glazes so gradually that contours dissolve into smoky haze?',
    options: ['Chiaroscuro', 'Sfumato', 'Impasto', 'Encaustic'],
    answer: 1,
  },
  {
    category: 'Baroque',
    q: 'Which Baroque painter revolutionized art with tenebrism — extreme darkness pierced by a single dramatic spotlight on figures?',
    options: ['Peter Paul Rubens', 'Johannes Vermeer', 'Caravaggio', 'Rembrandt'],
    answer: 2,
  },
  {
    category: 'Impressionism',
    q: 'The Impressionist movement got its name (mockingly) from which painting?',
    options: ['Water Lilies', 'The Gleaners', 'Impression, Sunrise', 'The Dance'],
    answer: 2,
  },
  {
    category: 'Philosophy',
    q: 'Which philosopher argued that art is "twice removed from truth" — a copy of a copy of eternal Forms?',
    options: ['Aristotle', 'Immanuel Kant', 'Plato', 'Hegel'],
    answer: 2,
  },
  {
    category: 'Post-Impressionism',
    q: 'Pointillism — applying tiny dots of pure unmixed color that blend in the eye — was developed by which artist?',
    options: ['Vincent van Gogh', 'Paul Gauguin', 'Paul Cézanne', 'Georges Seurat'],
    answer: 3,
  },
  {
    category: 'Gallery',
    q: '"The Starry Night" was painted while Van Gogh was staying at which location?',
    options: ['A Paris studio', 'Amsterdam lodgings', 'An asylum in Saint-Rémy-de-Provence', 'A beach house in Arles'],
